how I'm supposed to address you.

247
00:21:06,898 --> 00:21:08,206
Well, you're doing fine, love.

248
00:21:09,134 --> 00:21:11,580
Well, tools were always
on your Christmas list,

249
00:21:11,637 --> 00:21:14,846
but I had no idea that you knew
how to actually make anything.

250
00:21:14,906 --> 00:21:16,783
He's a beaver, Mom. That's what they do.

251
00:21:16,842 --> 00:21:18,321
Yeah. Spot on, mate.

252
00:21:18,810 --> 00:21:22,587
But, you know, Walter
wasn't half-bad himself, at one time.

253
00:21:22,648 --> 00:21:24,594
Yeah? Who taught him?

254
00:21:24,650 --> 00:21:25,924
I suppose he taught himself.

255
00:21:26,685 --> 00:21:29,222
He was about your age, yeah. Cub Scouts.

256
00:21:29,288 --> 00:21:31,666
He and his pop were supposed
to make a race car for a contest.

257
00:21:32,057 --> 00:21:34,936
Except, his pop weren't around
so he had to do it himself.

258
00:21:35,727 --> 00:21:37,400
Where was his dad?

259
00:21:42,734 --> 00:21:45,613
He got very sad and he had an accident.

260
00:21:45,704 --> 00:21:48,014
You mean Grandpa Jerry
from the graveyard?

261
00:21:48,707 --> 00:21:53,053
Right-o. Anyway, Walter had Grandpa's
tools but no clue how to use them.

262
00:21:53,979 --> 00:21:56,619
So, what he ended up making was so awful

263
00:21:56,682 --> 00:22:00,095
that it looked like he'd screwed a set
of wheels onto a piece of dog crap.

264
00:22:01,353 --> 00:22:03,196
And you know what the other kids called it?

265
00:22:03,889 --> 00:22:07,427
The Turd. That was generous, mate.

266
00:22:07,759 --> 00:22:11,639
One lady threw up all over herself
just 'cause it got close to her.

267
00:22:12,431 --> 00:22:14,911
But when it came to racing...

268
00:22:15,667 --> 00:22:16,668
What?

269
00:22:17,469 --> 00:22:19,278
The Turd could not be beat.

270
00:22:19,671 --> 00:22:21,708
-Sweet.
-Yeah.

271
00:22:21,773 --> 00:22:23,411
-Dad?
-Yeah, mate?

272
00:22:24,443 --> 00:22:27,287
-Can we make a Turd?
-Yeah, anytime, mate.

273
00:22:27,846 --> 00:22:30,053
You give the word, we'll make the Turd.

274
00:22:30,816 --> 00:22:31,817
Yeah.

275
00:22:33,618 --> 00:22:35,291
Good night, Beaver.

276
00:22:36,655 --> 00:22:37,656
Good night, mate.

277
00:22:44,996 --> 00:22:45,997
Good night.

278
00:22:48,867 --> 00:22:50,540
Good night, Beaver.

279
00:22:52,537 --> 00:22:54,517
-Hello?
-Norah.

280
00:22:54,573 --> 00:22:55,916
Hey, it's Porter.

281
00:22:58,844 --> 00:23:00,619
Listen, what I said earlier...

282
00:23:00,679 --> 00:23:03,319
-So, are you going to help me or not?
-Yeah.

283
00:23:05,417 --> 00:23:11,857
But for this sort of thing, I'm going to have
to ask you for, like, $500?

284
00:23:12,691 --> 00:23:13,692
Done.

285
00:23:14,493 --> 00:23:16,871
Wow. Would you have gone $1,000?

286
00:23:17,496 --> 00:23:19,339
-Oh, yeah.
-How about a million?

287
00:23:19,398 --> 00:23:20,502
Can you come by tomorrow?

288
00:23:21,400 --> 00:23:24,210
Yeah! Yeah, yeah, yeah. Absolutely.

289
00:23:25,604 --> 00:23:30,383
You know, I didn't... Look, I...
We're cool, right? I... I'm...

290
00:23:30,709 --> 00:23:32,620
You've never even said a word to me,
you know, and...

291
00:23:32,677 --> 00:23:34,054
-Porter?
-And it's not like we

292
00:23:34,112 --> 00:23:37,355
-know each other or anything... Yeah.
-Just come by tomorrow.

293
00:23:38,383 --> 00:23:40,124
-Okay.
-Okay.

294
00:23:42,387 --> 00:23:44,196
Good night! See you soon.

295
00:24:48,820 --> 00:24:52,358
Trust me, mate. Today will set you free.

296
00:25:22,587 --> 00:25:24,032
What the hell is this?

297
00:25:24,089 --> 00:25:25,500
I have no idea.

298
00:25:25,557 --> 00:25:27,662
This is layoffs, isn't it? Goddamn China.

299
00:25:27,726 --> 00:25:29,330
Nobody's getting laid off.

300
00:25:31,329 --> 00:25:32,330
Get rid of you lot?

301
00:25:32,664 --> 00:25:34,371
I'd have no one to boss around, yeah?

302
00:25:36,635 --> 00:25:38,376
-The boss woke up and brought a friend.

303
00:25:39,037 --> 00:25:43,816
I think we should maintain some respect
until Mr. Black tells us...

304
00:25:44,175 --> 00:25:45,210
Good morning, all.

305
00:25:47,178 --> 00:25:49,089
I assume you all got the cards.

306
00:25:49,881 --> 00:25:52,487
If not, allow me to briefly explain.

307
00:25:53,485 --> 00:25:57,661
Walter Black ascended
to CEO of this company two years ago.

308
00:25:57,722 --> 00:26:03,195
Not through any particular skill or merit,
but because Walter was next in line

309
00:26:03,328 --> 00:26:07,868
rather than our infinitely more qualified VP
standing right here.

310
00:26:08,466 --> 00:26:09,467
Hello, love.

311
00:26:09,534 --> 00:26:13,778
It was a job Walter was, well,
ill-prepared to handle.

312
00:26:14,839 --> 00:26:16,250
Basically, well...

313
00:26:17,676 --> 00:26:19,212
Walter's been a loser.

314
00:26:20,278 --> 00:26:26,888
Which is why, as of now, he is resigning
and putting me in charge.

315
00:26:27,352 --> 00:26:31,391
So, before you decide to run me out on a rail
with all the flaming torches and pitchforks,

316
00:26:31,456 --> 00:26:37,600
hear me out, give me five minutes,
then you may tear me to shreds, if you like.

317
00:26:37,696 --> 00:26:42,441
First, I will be ceding control
of all individual projects

318
00:26:42,500 --> 00:26:44,002
back to the teams themselves.

319
00:26:44,069 --> 00:26:45,412
That means you will be free

320
00:26:45,503 --> 00:26:49,041
and entrusted to do the jobs
you was hired to do in the first place.

321
00:26:49,107 --> 00:26:50,108
Hello, Hank.

322
00:26:50,175 --> 00:26:53,850
Second, we will revamp, revitalize, re-launch

323
00:26:54,012 --> 00:26:57,550
at the International Game
and Toy Manufacturers Expo

324
00:26:57,616 --> 00:27:00,392
in six weeks' time.

325
00:27:00,819 --> 00:27:05,791
Now, I know there's a very high degree
of skepticism about my ability to lead.

326
00:27:06,157 --> 00:27:07,431
Isn't that right?

327
00:27:07,492 --> 00:27:10,871
I mean, middle-aged man
with his arm stuck up my bum. Right?

328
00:27:11,096 --> 00:27:15,272
Who wouldn't doubt me?
But I'll make you the following deal.

329
00:27:15,333 --> 00:27:19,975
You give me two weeks, just two,
and at the end of that time,

330
00:27:20,038 --> 00:27:23,281
anyone who wants to resign
will receive severance pay

331
00:27:23,341 --> 00:27:25,582
and a glowing letter of recommendation.

332
00:27:25,644 --> 00:27:28,818
-No questions asked, no exceptions.
- Excuse me?

333
00:27:28,947 --> 00:27:30,392
And who exactly are you supposed to be?

334
00:27:31,149 --> 00:27:34,062
Bollocks. Did I forget to introduce myself?

335
00:27:34,653 --> 00:27:37,532
You may simply call me the Beaver.

336
00:27:45,330 --> 00:27:46,400
Impressive.

337
00:27:48,633 --> 00:27:49,634
So, what do you need to know?

338
00:27:51,369 --> 00:27:55,044
Well, I guess the first thing is,
what do you want to say?

339
00:27:58,009 --> 00:27:59,886
Well, that's kind of the problem.

340
00:28:00,211 --> 00:28:03,420
I mean, I got good grades. Big deal.
What do I know?

341
00:28:03,481 --> 00:28:07,258
Okay. Well, how do you want people to feel
when you're done?

342
00:28:07,519 --> 00:28:13,128
I guess I just want them to feel not

343
00:28:14,125 --> 00:28:15,399
let down.

344
00:28:15,527 --> 00:28:16,528
"Not let down."

345
00:28:17,028 --> 00:28:18,336
That's powerful.

346
00:28:19,931 --> 00:28:22,104
"I'm excited, pumped. How are you doing?"

347
00:28:22,167 --> 00:28:24,204
"Me? I'm not let down."

348
00:28:25,470 --> 00:28:28,280
I told you that I suck. This is why I need you.

349
00:28:28,339 --> 00:28:31,877
Okay, well, you're a cheerleader,
notorious hothead.

350
00:28:31,943 --> 00:28:33,980
Could we talk about you getting expelled
from the eighth grade?

351
00:28:35,880 --> 00:28:37,325
How did you find out about that?

352
00:28:38,083 --> 00:28:40,188
No secrets on the Internet.

353
00:28:40,719 --> 00:28:41,720
What did you do?

354
00:28:41,786 --> 00:28:43,026
Did you steal some encyclopedias?

355
00:28:43,088 --> 00:28:45,125
-Chew some nicotine gum?
-No.

356
00:28:45,190 --> 00:28:47,101
What? Tease a fat kid?

357
00:28:47,625 --> 00:28:48,626
Shut up.

358
00:28:49,127 --> 00:28:50,197
All right. So, what is it?

359
00:28:52,831 --> 00:28:54,139
I was tagging.

360
00:28:56,835 --> 00:28:58,075
Tagging?

361
00:28:59,704 --> 00:29:00,910
Like...

362
00:29:04,609 --> 00:29:05,610
Like graffiti tagging?

363
00:29:06,144 --> 00:29:10,183
More like art. It was just illegal.

364
00:29:12,117 --> 00:29:15,587
Where's all this rebel-artist shit now?

365
00:29:16,121 --> 00:29:18,123
That was a long time ago.

366
00:29:18,990 --> 00:29:22,460
You still have some, don't you? Yeah.

367
00:29:22,660 --> 00:29:24,765
-Show me, please.
-No.

368
00:29:25,730 --> 00:29:28,870
If you show me, I will write you a speech
that you could free Tibet with.

369
00:29:29,200 --> 00:29:30,304
Why do you want to see it so bad?

370
00:29:31,569 --> 00:29:33,276
Because I like to be surprised.

371
00:29:38,076 --> 00:29:40,420
-We have to be quick.
-All right.

372
00:29:42,313 --> 00:29:44,054
Whose room is this?

373
00:29:44,349 --> 00:29:45,657
No one's.

374
00:29:54,993 --> 00:29:56,199
Oh, wow.

375
00:30:06,771 --> 00:30:11,914
I like to do it big.
Like freeways, buildings, billboards.

376
00:30:13,211 --> 00:30:18,354
And fast.
Like I'm running a million miles an hour.

377
00:30:20,185 --> 00:30:21,721
No thinking, you know?

378
00:30:24,189 --> 00:30:25,429
Why did you stop?

379
00:30:29,194 --> 00:30:32,664
'Cause I got caught
and my mom couldn't take it.

380
00:30:33,531 --> 00:30:36,512
Anyway, I threw them all away.

381
00:30:36,568 --> 00:30:37,569
Someone must have liked them.

382
00:30:39,037 --> 00:30:41,881
Pulled them out of the trash, didn't they?

383
00:30:43,107 --> 00:30:45,246
-Who was it?
- What are you doing in here?

384
00:30:47,412 --> 00:30:50,325
I was just showing Porter around the house.

385
00:30:52,183 --> 00:30:54,424
He's on the math team with me.

386
00:30:54,886 --> 00:30:56,627
-Right.
-Time to go.

387
00:30:59,791 --> 00:31:02,601
Hey, I'm sorry about my mom.

388
00:31:03,728 --> 00:31:05,935
-She's just, you know...
-That's fine.

389
00:31:10,535 --> 00:31:12,310
You know, you are

390
00:31:14,439 --> 00:31:15,850
so much weirder...

391
00:31:19,310 --> 00:31:22,848
Not weird, I just mean, like,
different, I guess.

392
00:31:23,448 --> 00:31:26,861
You're a lot more different
than I thought you'd be.

393
00:31:27,385 --> 00:31:30,093
You know, for someone I'm paying
a lot of money to write a speech for me,

394
00:31:30,154 --> 00:31:31,656
you're not very articulate.

395
00:31:32,757 --> 00:31:33,895
I'm much better on paper.

396
00:31:35,026 --> 00:31:36,369
We'll see.

397
00:31:37,495 --> 00:31:41,375
Thank you for not laughing, I guess.

398
00:31:41,833 --> 00:31:42,834
I wouldn't do that.

399
00:31:43,101 --> 00:31:44,739
I wouldn't laugh.

400
00:31:45,637 --> 00:31:46,707
Good.

401
00:31:49,173 --> 00:31:50,777
Very, very good.

402
00:32:05,790 --> 00:32:10,899
We salute at the threshold
of the North Sea in my mind

403
00:32:11,663 --> 00:32:14,940
And a nod to the boredom that drove me here

404
00:32:14,999 --> 00:32:19,072
To face the tide and swim

405
00:32:19,771 --> 00:32:23,810
I swim, oh, swim

406
00:32:24,075 --> 00:32:28,319
And, eventually,
what seems strange becomes common.

407
00:32:29,447 --> 00:32:32,587
What seemed impossible becomes real.

408
00:32:32,650 --> 00:32:37,895
Up to my knees now,
do I wait? Do I dive?

409
00:32:38,556 --> 00:32:43,528
The sea has seen my like before though
it's my first and perhaps last time

410
00:32:44,462 --> 00:32:49,844
Let's call me a Baptist,
call this the drowning of the past

411
00:32:50,268 --> 00:32:55,479
She's there on the shoreline
Throwing stones at my back

412
00:32:55,540 --> 00:32:58,953
So swim until you can't see land

413
00:32:59,010 --> 00:33:01,820
Swim until you can’t see land

414
00:33:01,879 --> 00:33:04,985
Swim until you can’t see land

415
00:33:05,049 --> 00:33:08,792
Are you a man or are you a bag of sand?

416
00:33:11,389 --> 00:33:15,337
Until things almost
start to feel the way they used to.

417
00:33:18,696 --> 00:33:19,902
Fixed it, love. Working like a charm.

418
00:33:19,964 --> 00:33:22,171
It's like it's all brand new.

419
00:33:30,675 --> 00:33:34,213
-Walter. Walter, wake up. Wake up.
-Mmm. What?

420
00:33:34,412 --> 00:33:38,019
It's Henry. He snuck out of his room.
He's down in the garage again by himself.

421
00:33:38,082 --> 00:33:40,323
Well, tell him to come to bed.

422
00:33:40,385 --> 00:33:45,232
I know. I tell him every night, but he needs
to hear it from, you know, you.

423
00:33:46,190 --> 00:33:47,191
Yeah.

424
00:33:49,260 --> 00:33:50,603
I'm on it.

425
00:33:54,399 --> 00:33:57,608
Whoa, where are you going
this time of night?

426
00:33:57,668 --> 00:33:59,875
I'm gonna tell the little guy
to knock it off so I can sleep.

427
00:33:59,937 --> 00:34:00,938
Right.

428
00:34:01,039 --> 00:34:04,418
I was going to the same place.
Come on. Let's triple-team him.

429
00:34:05,376 --> 00:34:08,550
That's okay.
You've got your little furry friend.

430
00:34:11,682 --> 00:34:12,683
Good night.

431
00:34:22,060 --> 00:34:23,869
What are you making besides a racket?

432
00:34:23,928 --> 00:34:24,929
You couldn't sleep, either?

433
00:34:25,830 --> 00:34:29,073
Well, actually, mate,
I was having a brilliant kip

434
00:34:29,133 --> 00:34:31,340
till you started banging away.

435
00:34:32,170 --> 00:34:34,047
I just had this idea.

436
00:34:34,105 --> 00:34:36,585
Oh, yeah?
Well, let's have the idea in the morning.

437
00:34:37,175 --> 00:34:39,712
Just 10 more minutes, please?

438
00:34:39,777 --> 00:34:41,415
Ten more minutes, all right, yes.

439
00:34:41,479 --> 00:34:45,928
But no more mucking about with tools
when I'm not around. it's not safe.

440
00:34:46,084 --> 00:34:48,758
Or when your mother's asked you not to.
Or at night.

441
00:34:48,820 --> 00:34:52,700
Or in a toilet.
Or when you're climbing Mount Everest.

442
00:34:53,191 --> 00:34:54,761
Or picking your nose. Agreed?

443
00:34:55,359 --> 00:34:57,236
-Agreed.
-There you go.

444
00:34:59,964 --> 00:35:03,138
Can you talk to me? I like it when you talk.

445
00:35:04,068 --> 00:35:05,638
What do you want me to talk about?

446
00:35:05,703 --> 00:35:07,182
Doesn't matter. Just talk.

447
00:35:08,739 --> 00:35:10,650
You have a funny voice.

448
00:35:11,642 --> 00:35:13,952
You're quite easily entertained, aren't you?

449
00:35:17,582 --> 00:35:22,088
Give you a buzz saw, a block of wood,
and some chatter...

450
00:35:31,095 --> 00:35:32,597
Hey, Walter, did you talk to him?

451
00:35:32,930 --> 00:35:35,911
Yes, and everything's fine.
He'll stick to the schedule.

452
00:35:36,167 --> 00:35:37,305
What's going on?

453
00:35:37,435 --> 00:35:41,076
I've had a breakthrough, love.
Got to get to work right away.

454
00:35:41,172 --> 00:35:42,173
Now?

455
00:35:42,240 --> 00:35:43,810
Not a moment to spare!

456
00:35:47,111 --> 00:35:48,818
You're a goddess.

457
00:36:01,058 --> 00:36:03,504
Sir? You're in early.

458
00:36:03,561 --> 00:36:05,871
Just the woman I wanted to see.

459
00:36:06,931 --> 00:36:07,932
Have a look at this.

460
00:36:09,033 --> 00:36:11,843
Now, we need to get started on this
right away.

461
00:36:12,370 --> 00:36:13,815
It's a beaver?

462
00:36:14,872 --> 00:36:15,907
It's the future.

463
00:36:16,374 --> 00:36:17,375
This?

464
00:36:17,642 --> 00:36:19,815
The Talking Beaver
Woodworking Set.

465
00:36:20,178 --> 00:36:22,988
You get your basic tools, a block of wood

466
00:36:23,047 --> 00:36:25,618
and a talking beaver
to work right alongside of you.

467
00:36:26,083 --> 00:36:27,391
You should see the kids, love.

468
00:36:27,451 --> 00:36:29,522
I mean, they've got their cell phones
and their computers,

469
00:36:29,587 --> 00:36:32,158
but, wow, you give them a block of wood,
a hammer and a saw?

470
00:36:32,223 --> 00:36:33,566
Bob's their bleeding auntie.

471
00:36:33,624 --> 00:36:36,161
Their poor little brains are starving
for something like this.

472
00:36:36,227 --> 00:36:39,640
So, you're talking about a new product line
for what? Christmas?

473
00:36:39,697 --> 00:36:42,678
Christmas? I'm talking about right now,
woman. Today.

474
00:36:43,401 --> 00:36:44,880
This morning.

475
00:36:45,970 --> 00:36:48,541
I guess there could be an ancillary market
in more tools.

476
00:36:49,407 --> 00:36:51,318
Maybe pre-cut lumber pieces?

477
00:36:51,375 --> 00:36:53,412
Sort of like Lego kits but made of wood.

478
00:36:53,477 --> 00:36:56,117
And you can work them
into shapes on your own.

479
00:36:56,380 --> 00:36:58,587
Now, that's using your scone.

480
00:36:58,916 --> 00:37:00,896
Not just made out of wood, is it? Let's go.

481
00:37:01,152 --> 00:37:02,495
But this would mean, I mean,

482
00:37:02,553 --> 00:37:06,399
even if we could get one ready in time,
this is all we would have for the Expo.

483
00:37:06,691 --> 00:37:08,364
That's all we'll need, my darling.

484
00:37:19,036 --> 00:37:20,709
And for every person that points out

485
00:37:20,771 --> 00:37:22,614
that there's a rodent at the helm,

486
00:37:22,673 --> 00:37:28,248
there's another to remind him or her that
production has already increased by 35%.

487
00:37:28,613 --> 00:37:32,425
At the end of those first two weeks,
not one person resigns.

488
00:37:32,917 --> 00:37:33,918
Not one.

489
00:37:35,720 --> 00:37:37,597
Now, we're going to start with...

490
00:37:38,789 --> 00:37:43,033
The Beaver, as a core item,
along with endless project kits

491
00:37:43,494 --> 00:37:45,371
could produce an exponential return.

492
00:37:45,796 --> 00:37:50,176
The question is, do we want
to continue struggling merely to survive,

493
00:37:50,234 --> 00:37:55,149
or do we want to embrace something new,
something different,

494
00:37:55,239 --> 00:37:57,310
and see where it takes us?

495
00:38:00,711 --> 00:38:03,851
Once again,
our beloved Jerry Co.

