587
00:45:31,361 --> 00:45:32,362
But I like it.

588
00:45:33,130 --> 00:45:35,872
It's your paper-writing dollars at work.

589
00:45:44,541 --> 00:45:45,576
What was that for?

590
00:45:46,009 --> 00:45:47,955
You said you liked to be surprised.

591
00:45:50,547 --> 00:45:52,652
-Ready?
-For what?

592
00:46:06,663 --> 00:46:08,370
It's a great place.

593
00:46:09,399 --> 00:46:11,970
It's kind of scary but beautiful.

594
00:46:14,438 --> 00:46:18,352
Look, I wasn't sure which color you liked,
so I kind of got everything.

595
00:46:18,408 --> 00:46:20,513
I hope you like sunburst yellow.

596
00:46:21,378 --> 00:46:23,949
Porter? Porter, come on.
What are you doing?

597
00:46:24,281 --> 00:46:25,954
Is this fantastic, or what?

598
00:46:26,016 --> 00:46:28,758
Are you kidding?
it's awesome, but I'm not going to touch it.

599
00:46:29,253 --> 00:46:31,233
-Why not?
-Because.

600
00:46:33,023 --> 00:46:36,493
-Because, what? Why not?
-Because I don't want to.

601
00:46:38,162 --> 00:46:40,665
Come on, Norah.
You have this amazing thing that you do.

602
00:46:41,565 --> 00:46:45,672
You just put all of yourself out there.
All I can do is sound like other people.

603
00:46:46,570 --> 00:46:48,413
-I know you have something to say.
-Okay.

604
00:46:48,739 --> 00:46:52,152
-Knock yourself out. You do it.
-Come on.

605
00:46:53,343 --> 00:46:55,050
No. I don't paint.

606
00:46:55,746 --> 00:46:58,693
Why not?
You're so good at being other people.

607
00:46:58,749 --> 00:47:02,788
-Well, maybe if I could paint I would, but...
-Porter, just start.

608
00:47:04,254 --> 00:47:05,358
Okay.

609
00:47:09,293 --> 00:47:11,773
What are you going to do?
Write "Norah + Porter forever"?

610
00:47:13,664 --> 00:47:15,701
Because that'd be pretty cute.

611
00:47:46,063 --> 00:47:47,269
Right?

612
00:47:51,668 --> 00:47:54,615
-That's what you've been wanting to say.
-No.

613
00:47:54,671 --> 00:47:57,811
You wrote 400 pages of notes.
Not one word about him?

614
00:47:57,875 --> 00:48:00,287
What happened to my brother
is none of your business.

615
00:48:00,377 --> 00:48:01,412
Do you understand?

616
00:48:01,478 --> 00:48:03,321
I just thought there was something
you wanted to say

617
00:48:03,380 --> 00:48:05,360
and you didn't know how.

618
00:48:06,316 --> 00:48:07,624
It's none of your business.

619
00:48:08,585 --> 00:48:10,690
What kind of person
does something like this?

620
00:48:11,288 --> 00:48:12,995
What's the matter with you?

621
00:48:28,772 --> 00:48:30,183
Go on. Open it.

622
00:48:31,608 --> 00:48:34,555
Henry helped me, which basically means

623
00:48:34,645 --> 00:48:37,854
that I bought the wood
and he did all the work.

624
00:48:43,754 --> 00:48:45,461
It's a memory box.

625
00:48:46,657 --> 00:48:48,364
It's very nice. Thank you.

626
00:48:48,992 --> 00:48:50,403
Look inside.

627
00:48:55,899 --> 00:48:59,437
I thought it was important
to remind ourselves of how things were.

628
00:48:59,569 --> 00:49:02,243
How things should be.

629
00:49:13,817 --> 00:49:17,094
Walter. No, no, no. it's okay. it's okay.

630
00:49:20,958 --> 00:49:22,528
Is this what you want?

631
00:49:23,360 --> 00:49:25,704
Is this progress? Christ, woman!

632
00:49:26,863 --> 00:49:29,605
He's suffering from depression,
not amnesia!

633
00:49:29,666 --> 00:49:31,737
You think the problem
is he can't remember these things?

634
00:49:32,235 --> 00:49:35,045
-No.
-He can't go back. Don't you see that?

635
00:49:35,973 --> 00:49:40,251
This is all in the past, and dredging it up...
Do you know where this leads?

636
00:49:40,911 --> 00:49:43,255
You know where this Walter goes?

637
00:49:43,313 --> 00:49:47,887
To a 10th floor balcony,
tied to a shower curtain rod.

638
00:49:47,951 --> 00:49:49,862
Is that what you want?

639
00:49:50,787 --> 00:49:53,927
You want the rest of your life
to be just like tonight?

640
00:49:53,991 --> 00:49:57,598
-Well, that was Walter.
-No, Walter. No, come on.

641
00:49:59,296 --> 00:50:01,936
Look at this. You really look at this.

642
00:50:03,834 --> 00:50:05,404
That's you, Walter.

643
00:50:06,603 --> 00:50:08,105
Remember that?

644
00:50:09,072 --> 00:50:14,044
When Porter was born, and he was so little?

645
00:50:14,644 --> 00:50:18,285
And they pulled him out of me,
and you stood right by him.

646
00:50:18,348 --> 00:50:19,418
You looked him right in the eye,

647
00:50:19,483 --> 00:50:21,190
and you let him know
that you weren't going anywhere,

648
00:50:21,251 --> 00:50:24,130
that you were staying right there
so he wouldn't be scared.

649
00:50:25,689 --> 00:50:28,670
Walter, that's you. That's the man I love.
That's the man I need.

650
00:50:30,861 --> 00:50:32,306
You're still inside there, honey.

651
00:50:33,997 --> 00:50:38,241
I know you're in there. We can go back.

652
00:50:38,301 --> 00:50:40,110
We can get back to the way
that we used to be.

653
00:50:40,170 --> 00:50:42,912
We are not going
down that street again, Meredith.

654
00:50:44,007 --> 00:50:48,285
This man is a dead end.
He's gone. He has to be.

655
00:50:49,146 --> 00:50:50,181
You get it?

656
00:50:51,314 --> 00:50:52,315
I fought for you.

657
00:50:53,083 --> 00:50:56,121
I practically breathed for you for two years
when you couldn't even get out of bed,

658
00:50:56,186 --> 00:50:59,292
and I will continue to fight for you
because I love you.

659
00:51:00,223 --> 00:51:03,329
I've got to know that you're coming back.
Come back to me, please.

660
00:51:04,127 --> 00:51:05,333
Walter?

661
00:51:07,030 --> 00:51:08,304
Walter?

662
00:51:21,812 --> 00:51:24,622
Norah, I can't take this again.

663
00:51:28,251 --> 00:51:29,491
Come on.

664
00:51:37,627 --> 00:51:40,130
Hello. We came as soon as we heard.

665
00:51:41,398 --> 00:51:44,811
I'm the Beaver,
and this is Porter's dad, Walter.

666
00:51:46,870 --> 00:51:49,646
Listen, we'll get it all sorted.
I'm here now so we'll take care of things.

667
00:51:50,040 --> 00:51:52,247
Have a nice safe drive home.

668
00:52:08,725 --> 00:52:09,726
Wait.

669
00:52:12,829 --> 00:52:16,140
Porter, mate, hang about. Come on.
We can discuss this. Come on.

670
00:52:16,199 --> 00:52:17,678
-Give me that thing!
-Calm down!

671
00:52:17,734 --> 00:52:20,044
-Give it to me! Goddamn it!
-Stop it!

672
00:52:20,103 --> 00:52:21,673
-Give me that thing!
-Stop!

673
00:52:21,738 --> 00:52:23,342
Leave him alone!

674
00:52:24,975 --> 00:52:29,788
Porter! Porter! Oh, my God.
Porter, are you okay? Are you all right?

675
00:52:30,280 --> 00:52:31,782
Porter, let me see your hands.
